<DOC><DOCNO> AP900408-0058 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-90 2102EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-08 0240</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0248</SECOND><HEAD>Low-Temperature Records Broken From Arkansas to Kentucky</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Temperatures dropped to record lows Sunday morning in 22 citiesfrom Arkansas to Pennsylvania, and springtime snow fell in Nevadaand Pennsylvania.   Rain extended from southern Idaho to northern Nevada andnorthwest Utah, with rain changing to snow in the mountains. Rainshowers fell from central Texas to the lower Texas coast.   Snow showers were scattered over central Pennsylvania, andAustin, Nevada, received 5 inches of snow in the six hours endingat 12 p.m. MDT.   The spring cold snap broke low-temperature records for the dateup to 91 years old in 18 cities, including Elkins, W.Va., where areading of 16 degrees snapped by 1 degree the record set in 1975.   Records were also broken in Apalachicola, Fla. (43 degrees, 46in 1971); Mena, Ark. (28, 32 in 1899 and 1909); Birmingham, Ala.(29, 32 in 1971); Nashville, Tenn. (27, 30 in 1936); and Richmond,Va. (28, 29 in 1950).   Parkersburg, Pa., where it was 24 degrees, was one of fourcities where low-temperature records were tied.   The cold snap didn't end Sunday. Frost and freeze warnings forSunday night were posted in parts of inland North and SouthCarolina.   The low temperature for the Lower 48 states was 16 degrees atElkins, W.Va. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT rangedfrom 34 degrees in Limestone, Maine, to 86 in Naples, Fla.</TEXT></DOC>